by Baizou » Tue Apr 27, 2021 10:11 am

503 wrote:I suppose that's another cliché: how many nations seem to portray tradition, morality, and religion on one side, and progressivism and secularism on the other. Religion need not be socially traditional, nor secularism necessarily lead to progressive change. Portraying all religious people as one entity and non-religious as another leads to generalisations.

In some respects, this was part of the origins of Baizou: a desire to shake-up typical boundaries and have ideas cross lines that seem to not usually get crossed. Hence Baizou's plurality Catholic population nonetheless consistently votes for the socially-progressive representatives and policies, in some ways thanks to the casuistic legacy of the early church in Baizou. Religion itself is a not-easily-boxed concept in Baizou, as the institutional eparchy and the indigenous Mahouzouhou tradition have maintained their unlikely alliance as "religions." The leaderships of the Liberals and Libertarians are relatively irreligious, but they're not secular progressives so much as neo-Enlightenment hyper-rationalists. The Lotuses and Marxists are interested in "tradition," but also yield to and press for progress respectively. Now, there are also some less disruptive forces in Baizou as well. The New Liberals and Socialists are pretty secular, and they're likewise very socially progressive. The Wakuna Restoration and New Conservatives are all about 'tradition, morals, etc.,' and they are anti-progressive. So there's some cliches and some attempts to reverse cliches. If we were to get speculative about the subconscious mind, I wonder if that was unconsciously part of my interest in videocassettepunk? After all, it's another way to cross seeming boundaries, putting the past together with the future.
